{"title_page": "Padre de Familia (film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name     = Padre de Familia\n| image    = Padre de Coco.jpg\n| caption  = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Adolfo Alix Jr.]]\n| starring = {{ubl|[[Nora Aunor]]|[[Coco Martin]]}}\n| producer = [[Rodel Nacianceno]]\n| screenplay  =  {{ubl|Nikki Bunquin|Jerry Gracio}}\n| story       = {{ubl|Ralston Jover|Adolfo Alix Jr.}}\n| music       = Von de Guzman\n| cinematography =  Albert Banzon\n| editing  = {{ubl|Renewin Alano|Benjamin Tolentino}}\n| studio   = CCM Creatives\n| distributor = [[Star Cinema]]\n| released = {{Film date|2016|02|20}}\n| runtime  = 96 minutes\n| country  = [[Philippines]]\n| language = {{ubl|[[Filipino language|Filipino]]|[[English language|English]]}}\n| budget   =\n| gross    =\n}}\n\n'''''Padre de Familia''''' is a 2016 [[independent film|independent]] [[family film|family]] [[drama film]], starring [[Nora Aunor]] and [[Coco Martin]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Nora Aunor shares screen with Coco, Jasmine|url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/129305/nora-aunor-shares-screen-with-coco-jasmine|publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=12 January 2014|accessdate=22 January 2014|first=Bayani Jr.|last=San Diego}}</ref> It is the story of an [[Overseas Filipino Worker|Overseas Filipino Worker (OFW)]], Noel ([[Coco Martin]]) who has  to assume the responsibility of being the breadwinner of the family after his father went missing.  Likewise, it is also the story of the housewife, Aida ([[Nora Aunor]]) who has to assume the head of the family because the husband went away and never came back. The film has its premiere at selected cinemas in [[Europe]] and the [[Middle East]].\n\n==Plot==\n\nThe film starts with Noel ([[Coco Martin]]) leaving for [[Malaysia]] as an [[Overseas Filipino Worker|OFW]], he lands a job as a taxi driver and meets a woman named Pia ([[Julia Montes]]), who was crying as she rode the cab. Meanwhile, in the Philippines, Noel's mother, Aida ([[Nora Aunor]]) is receiving his remittances and gifts so she could take care of his siblings ([[Miles Ocampo]] and [[Manuel Chua]]), and the extended family like his hot-headed aunt Ramona ([[Rosanna Roces]]) and his grandmother ([[Anita Linda]]). \n\nPia rides Noel's cab for the second time and he discovers that she is from the Philippines like him. The two start dating after seeing each other more from then. He tells her about his father who also worked as an OFW but never returned, pushing him to work abroad as the new breadwinner of the family. Later on, she tells Noel that she has a partner and a child back home, which Noel didn't seem to mind.\n\nAida receives a letter which she appeared not to expect getting. After receiving it, she starts shopping for new clothes and grooming herself. She also meets Job ([[Joem Bascon]]), a much younger guy who works at the market and falls in love with him. The conflict began when Aida decided to take Job to be her partner, and took the young man to live with the entire family \u2013 much to the dismay of Ramona. \n\nThe plot thickens when Pia decides to leave Noel and go back to the Philippines after her work contract in Malaysia ended. Noel also went home one day and gets furious upon finding out that his mother is cheating on his father with a younger man. The content of the letter Aida received was revealed when she responded to her son's anger. They find out that Ben ([[Joel Torre]]) is alive, so Noel went to where his father was and took him home. He also searched for Pia and found out that her husband Raymond ([[Baron Geisler]]) is abusive, so he makes an effort to take her away from him. However, the husband finds out and beats him up.\n\nLater on, Ramona learns that Aida has not been paying the bills to get their house back after it had been mortgaged. This results to a feud that gives the grandmother a heart attack, eventually killing her. Ben tells the family that the money Noel has been giving to Aida went to his medication and new family, and that she was not spending it for Job. Noel and his mother sort things out right before Raymond set their house on fire.\n\nThe story ends with Noel and his family, finally together with Pia and her child in a new house, with Noel getting ready to go back to Malaysia once again to work and support them financially.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Nora Aunor]]<ref name=\"Cast\">{{cite news|url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/movies/13203/coco-martin-and-nora-aunor-co-star-in-upcoming-film-padre-de-pamilya|title=Coco Martin and Nora Aunor co-star in upcoming film Padre de Pamilya|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal|PEP]]|date=12 January 2014|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> as Aida Santiago\n* [[Coco Martin]]<ref name=\"Cast\" /> as Noel Santiago\n* [[Julia Montes]]<ref name=\"Cast\" /> as Pia\n* [[Joel Torre]]<ref name=\"Cast\" /> as Ben Santiago\n* [[Rosanna Roces]]<ref name=\"Cast\" /> as Ramona Santiago\n* [[Joem Bascon]]<ref name=\"Cast\" /> as Job\n* [[Baron Geisler]]<ref name=\"Cast\" /> as Raymond\n* [[Anita Linda]]<ref name=\"Cast\" /> as Lola Eva\n* [[Miles Ocampo]] as Tana Santiago\n* [[Manuel Chua]] as Caloy Santiago\n* Jess Mendoza as Tana's boyfriend\n* Paolo Diangson as Noel's son\n* Janvier Daily as Matador\n* Sunshine Teodoro as Saleswoman\n* Armand Reyes as Ben's neighbor \n* Malou Crisologo as Debt collector\n\n==Production==\nThe film was based on a concept by Coco Martin who drew from his experiences as an OFW in [[Canada]]. Nora Aunor was the first and original choice to play the lead actress alongside Martin. She initially had to beg off the project due to being busy with other projects.<ref name=\"casting\">{{cite news|url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/23196/coco-martin-sarah-geronimo-were-supposed-to-play-clark-and-leah-in-emon-the-wings-of-loveem|title=Coco Martin, Sarah Geronimo were supposed to play Clark and Leah in On The Wings Of Love|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal|PEP]]|first=Nikko|last=Tuazon|date=1 March 2016|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nWith the film's release then uncertain, the concept was turned into a teleserye which necessitated a change in the female lead to co-star with Martin. [[Judy Ann Santos]] was approached to be Martin's leading lady. Santos, however, turned down the offer due to unexpected pregnancy. [[Sarah Geronimo]] was also approached for the role of leading lady but also had to turn down the offer due to scheduling conflicts. Martin also ended up being busy with his teleserye, ''[[Ang Probinsyano]]''.<ref name=\"casting\"/>\n\nThe proposed teleserye, ''[[On the Wings of Love (TV series)|On the Wings of Love]]'' starring [[James Reid (entertainer)|James Reid]] and [[Nadine Lustre]],<ref name=\"casting\"/> aired on [[ABS-CBN]] and wrapped up around the same time that ''Padre de Familia'' was released in theaters.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{imdb name|5641510|Padre de Familia (2016)}}\n\n{{Adolfo Alix Jr.}}\n\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:Philippine films]]\n[[Category:Tagalog-language films]]\n[[Category:Star Cinema films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name     = Padre de Familia\n| image    = Padre de Coco.jpg\n| caption  = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Adolfo Alix Jr.]]\n| starring = {{ubl|[[Nora Aunor]]|[[Coco Martin]]}}\n| producer = [[Rodel Nacianceno]]\n| screenplay  =  {{ubl|Nikki Bunquin|Jerry Gracio}}\n| story       = {{ubl|Ralston Jover|Adolfo Alix Jr.}}\n| music       = Von de Guzman\n| cinematography =  Albert Banzon\n| editing  = {{ubl|Renewin Alano|Benjamin Tolentino}}\n| studio   = CCM Creatives\n| distributor = [[Star Cinema]]\n| released = {{Film date|2016|02|20}}\n| runtime  = 96 minutes\n| country  = [[Philippines]]\n| language = {{ubl|[[Filipino language|Filipino]]|[[English language|English]]}}\n| budget   =\n| gross    =\n}}\n\n'''''Padre de Familia''''' is a 2016 [[independent film|independent]] [[family film|family]] [[drama film]], starring [[Nora Aunor]] and [[Coco Martin]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Nora Aunor shares screen with Coco, Jasmine|url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/129305/nora-aunor-shares-screen-with-coco-jasmine|publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=12 January 2014|accessdate=22 January 2014|first=Bayani Jr.|last=San Diego}}</ref> It is the story of an [[Overseas Filipino Worker|Overseas Filipino Worker (OFW)]], Noel ([[Coco Martin]]) who has  to assume the responsibility of being the breadwinner of the family after his father went missing.  Likewise, it is also the story of the housewife, Aida ([[Nora Aunor]]) who has to assume the head of the family because the husband went away and never came back. The film has its premiere at selected cinemas in [[Europe]] and the [[Middle East]].\n\n==Plot==\n\nThe film starts with Noel ([[Coco Martin]]) leaving for [[Malaysia]] as an [[Overseas Filipino Worker|OFW]], he lands a job as a taxi driver and meets a woman named Pia ([[Julia Montes]]), who was crying as she rode the cab. Meanwhile, in the Philippines, Noel's mother, Aida ([[Nora Aunor]]) is receiving his remittances and gifts so she could take care of his siblings ([[Miles Ocampo]] and [[Manuel Chua]]), and the extended family like his hot-headed aunt Ramona ([[Rosanna Roces]]) and his grandmother ([[Anita Linda]]). \n\nPia rides Noel's cab for the second time and he discovers that she is from the Philippines like him. The two start dating after seeing each other more from then. He tells her about his father who also worked as an OFW but never returned, pushing him to work abroad as the new breadwinner of the family. Later on, she tells Noel that she has a partner and a child back home, which Noel didn't seem to mind.\n\nAida receives a letter which she appeared not to expect getting. After receiving it, she starts shopping for new clothes and grooming herself. She also meets Job ([[Joem Bascon]]), a much younger guy who works at the market and falls in love with him. The conflict began when Aida decided to take Job to be her partner, and took the young man to live with the entire family \u2013 much to the dismay of Ramona. \n\nThe plot thickens when Pia decides to leave Noel and go back to the Philippines after her work contract in Malaysia ended. Noel also went home one day and gets furious upon finding out that his mother is cheating on his father with a younger man. The content of the letter Aida received was revealed when she responded to her son's anger. They find out that Ben ([[Joel Torre]]) is alive, so Noel went to where his father was and took him home. He also searched for Pia and found out that her husband Raymond ([[Baron Geisler]]) is abusive, so he makes an effort to take her away from him. However, the husband finds out and beats him up.\n\nLater on, Ramona learns that Aida has not been paying the bills to get their house back after it had been mortgaged. This results to a feud that gives the grandmother a heart attack, eventually killing her. Ben tells the family that the money Noel has been giving to Aida went to his medication and new family, and that she was not spending it for Job. Noel and his mother sort things out right before Raymond set their house on fire.\n\nThe story ends with Noel and his family, finally together with Pia and her child in a new house, with Noel getting ready to go back to Malaysia once again to work and support them financially.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Nora Aunor]]<ref name=\"Cast>{{cite news|url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/movies/13203/coco-martin-and-nora-aunor-co-star-in-upcoming-film-padre-de-pamilya|title=Coco Martin and Nora Aunor co-star in upcoming film Padre de Pamilya|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal|PEP]]|date=12 January 2014|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> as Aida Santiago\n* [[Coco Martin]]<ref name=\"Cast/> as Noel Santiago\n* [[Julia Montes]]<ref name=\"Cast/> as Pia\n* [[Joel Torre]]<ref name=\"Cast/> as Ben Santiago\n* [[Rosanna Roces]]<ref name=\"Cast/> as Ramona Santiago\n* [[Joem Bascon]]<ref name=\"Cast/> as Job\n* [[Baron Geisler]]<ref name=\"Cast/> as Raymond\n* [[Anita Linda]]<ref name=\"Cast/> as Lola Eva\n* [[Miles Ocampo]] as Tana Santiago\n* [[Manuel Chua]] as Caloy Santiago\n* Jess Mendoza as Tana's boyfriend\n* Paolo Diangson as Noel's son\n* Janvier Daily as Matador\n* Sunshine Teodoro as Saleswoman\n* Armand Reyes as Ben's neighbor \n* Malou Crisologo as Debt collector\n\n==Production==\nThe film was based on a concept by Coco Martin who drew from his experiences as an OFW in [[Canada]]. Nora Aunor was the first and original choice to play the lead actress alongside Martin. She initially had to beg off the project due to being busy with other projects.<ref name=\"casting\">{{cite news|url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/23196/coco-martin-sarah-geronimo-were-supposed-to-play-clark-and-leah-in-emon-the-wings-of-loveem|title=Coco Martin, Sarah Geronimo were supposed to play Clark and Leah in On The Wings Of Love|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal|PEP]]|first=Nikko|last=Tuazon|date=1 March 2016|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nWith the film's release then uncertain, the concept was turned into a teleserye which necessitated a change in the female lead to co-star with Martin. [[Judy Ann Santos]] was approached to be Martin's leading lady. Santos, however, turned down the offer due to unexpected pregnancy. [[Sarah Geronimo]] was also approached for the role of leading lady but also had to turn down the offer due to scheduling conflicts. Martin also ended up being busy with his teleserye, ''[[Ang Probinsyano]]''.<ref name=\"casting\"/>\n\nThe proposed teleserye, ''[[On the Wings of Love (TV series)|On the Wings of Love]]'' starring [[James Reid (entertainer)|James Reid]] and [[Nadine Lustre]],<ref name=\"casting\"/> aired on [[ABS-CBN]] and wrapped up around the same time that ''Padre de Familia'' was released in theaters.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{imdb name|5641510|Padre de Familia (2016)}}\n\n{{Adolfo Alix Jr.}}\n\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:Philippine films]]\n[[Category:Tagalog-language films]]\n[[Category:Star Cinema films]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 -WP:WCWproject (Unbalanced quotes in ref name or illegal character.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Padre_de_Familia_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Brul\u00e9e River (Sainte-Anne River tributary)", "text_new": "{{short description|River in La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality, Quebec, Canada}}\n{{Other uses|Br\u00fbl\u00e9 River (disambiguation){{!}}Br\u00fbl\u00e9 River}}\n{{Infobox river\n| name               = Br\u00fbl\u00e9 River\n| name_native        = \n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = \n| image_caption      = \n| map                = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[Canada]]\n| subdivision_type2  = Province\n| subdivision_name2  = [[Quebec]]\n| subdivision_type3  = Region\n| subdivision_name3  = [[Capitale-Nationale]]\n| subdivision_type4  = [[Regional County Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name4  = [[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n| subdivision_type5  = [[Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name5  = [[Lac-Jacques-Cartier, Quebec|Lac-Jacques-Cartier]]\n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             = {{convert|20,1|km|mi|abbr=on}} \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= \n| discharge1_min     = \n| discharge1_avg     = \n| discharge1_max     = \n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = Fourchu lake\n| source1_location   = [[Lac-Jacques-Cartier, Quebec|Lac-Jacques-Cartier]]\n| source1_coordinates= {{coord|47.33381|-70.90714|type:river_region:CA-QC|format=dms|display=inline}}\n| source1_elevation  = 806 m\n| mouth              = [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)]]\n| mouth_location     = [[Lac-Jacques-Cartier, Quebec|Lac-Jacques-Cartier]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = {{coord|47.2275|-70.81389|type:river_region:CA-QC|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| mouth_elevation    = 370 m\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = \n| basin_size         = \n| tributaries_left   =(Upward from the mouth) Three unidentified streams, Lac de la Tour outlet, Caribou lake outlet.\n| tributaries_right  =(Upward from the mouth) Small unidentified stream, outlet of Lac Janot, outlet of Lac Br\u00fbl\u00e9.\n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = \n}}\nThe '''Rivi\u00e8re Br\u00fbl\u00e9''' is a tributary of the [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)|Sainte-Anne River]], flowing on the north bank of the [[Saint Lawrence River]], in the non-territory organized from [[Lac-Jacques-Cartier, Quebec|Lac-Jacques-Cartier]], in the [[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]], in the administrative region of [[Capitale-Nationale]], in the [[provinces and territories of Canada|province]] of [[Quebec]], in [[Canada]].\n\nThe southern part of this small valley is served on each side of the river by various forest roads. The upper part is served by a forest road which passes on the north side of the river. Forestry is the main economic activity in this valley; recreational tourism, second.\n\nThe surface of the Br\u00fbl\u00e9 River is generally frozen from the beginning of December until the end of March; however, safe traffic on the ice is generally from mid-December to mid-March. The upper part has a freezing period of about an additional week. The water level of the river varies with the seasons and the precipitation; the spring flood occurs in March or April.\n\n== Geography ==\nThe Br\u00fbl\u00e9 River takes its source at the confluence of Lake Fourchu, in the unorganized territory of [[Lac-Jacques-Cartier, Quebec|Lac-Jacques-Cartier]]. This lake has a marsh area on the west side and a high cliff on the north side and on the south side. The mouth of this lake is located at:\n* {{convert|4.6|km}} east of the course of the [[Savane River (Rivi\u00e8re des Neiges)|Savane River]];\n* {{convert|6.3|km}} west of the summit of Mont Raoul-Blanchard (altitude: {{convert|1159|m}});\n* {{convert|5.8|km}} northwest of the summit of Mont Bleu (altitude: {{convert|1150|m}});\n* {{convert|13.8|km}} north-west of the mouth of the Br\u00fbl\u00e9 river.\n\nFrom the mouth of Lac Fourchu, the course of the Br\u00fbl\u00e9 river descends on {{convert|20.1|km}}, with a drop of {{convert|436|m}}, according to the following segments:\n* {{convert|1,5|km}} east to the outlet (coming from the south) of Lac Br\u00fbl\u00e9;\n* {{convert|3.0|km}} to the east in a deep valley, up to a bend in the river;\n* {{convert|6,4|km}} to the south in a deep valley passing on the west side of Mont Raoul-Blanchard and Br\u00fbl\u00e9 mountain, then bending east to end in a small valley, until '' at the outlet (coming from the west) of Lac Janot;\n* {{convert|7.1|km}} towards the south-east with a drop of {{convert|99|m}}, forming some serpentines at the end of the segment where the current crosses a long series of rapids, until at a bend in the river;\n* {{convert|2.1|km}} towards the northeast by crossing several series of rapids, to its mouth.<ref name=Atlas>[https://atlas.gc.ca/toporama/en /index.html Atlas of Canada - Department of Natural Resources Canada - Rivi\u00e8re Br\u00fbl\u00e9 - Distance and altitude measurements established from the application of site measurements.]</ref>\n\nThe Br\u00fbl\u00e9 river flows on the southwest shore of the [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)]], in the unorganized territory of [[Lac-Jacques-Cartier, Quebec|Lac-Jacques-Cartier]], facing the northern limit of [[Saint-Tite-des-Caps]]. This confluence is located {{convert|13.1|km}} west of the northwest shore of the [[St. Lawrence River]], {{convert|20.5|km}} south west of the village center of [[Petite-Rivi\u00e8re-Saint-Fran\u00e7ois]] and {{convert|10.0|km}} north-west of the village center of [[Saint-Tite-des-Caps]].\n\nFrom the confluence of the Br\u00fbl\u00e9 river, the current flows over {{convert|27.5|km}} generally towards the southwest by the course of the [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)|Sainte-Anne River]], which crosses downtown [[Beaupr\u00e9, Quebec|Beaupr\u00e9]], to the northwest shore of the [[Saint Lawrence River]].<ref name=Atlas/>\n\n== Toponymy ==\nProbably born around 1592 in Champigny-sur-Marne in France, \u00c9tienne Br\u00fbl\u00e9 became an explorer and an interpreter in the Wendat (Huron) language. He arrived in the colony at the same time as [[Samuel de Champlain]], with whom he enlisted in 1608. Br\u00fbl\u00e9 was possibly the first European to have entered [[Huronia]]. He explored several territories including [[Georgian Bay]] and Lakes Huron, Ontario, Superior and Erie, where he traded furs for the French. During the illegal capture of [[Quebec (city) Quebec]] by the Kirke brothers in 1629, in a context of war between England and France, \u00c9tienne Brul\u00e9 went to the service of the English. Finally, the [[Treaty of Saint-Germain-en-Laye]] put an end to the conflict by restoring [[New France]] to [[France]], in 1632. Samuel de Champlain returned to the colony and accuses \u00c9tienne Br\u00fbl\u00e9 of treason in these terms: \"Here are those who betrayed their Roy & sold their homeland[\u2026]\". \u00c9tienne Brul\u00e9 then took refuge in [[Huronia]] where he was killed, in the year 1633.\n\nThe toponym \"Rivi\u00e8re Br\u00fbl\u00e9\" was formalized on December 13, 1996 at the Place Names Bank of the Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec.<ref>[http://www.toponymie.gouv.qc.ca/ct/ToposWeb/fiche.aspx?no_seq=167145 Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec - Bank of Place Names - Toponym: Rivi\u00e8re Br\u00fbl\u00e9]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n* [[Capitale-Nationale]], an administrative region\n* [[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n* [[Lac-Jacques-Cartier, Quebec|Lac-Jacques-Cartier]], an unorganized territory\n* [[Lac Br\u00fbl\u00e9 (Lac-Jacques-Cartier)]], a body of water\n* [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)]]\n* [[St. Lawrence River]]\n* [[List of rivers of Quebec]]\n\n{{Portal|Capitale-Nationale|lakes and streams}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Br\u00fbl\u00e9, river}}\n[[Category:Rivers of Capitale-Nationale]]\n[[Category:La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|River in La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality, Quebec, Canada}}\n{{Other uses|Br\u00fbl\u00e9 River (disambiguation){{!}}Br\u00fbl\u00e9 River}}\n{{Infobox river\n| name               = Br\u00fbl\u00e9 River\n| name_native        = \n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = \n| image_caption      = \n| map                = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[Canada]]\n| subdivision_type2  = Province\n| subdivision_name2  = [[Quebec]]\n| subdivision_type3  = Region\n| subdivision_name3  = [[Capitale-Nationale]]\n| subdivision_type4  = [[Regional County Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name4  = [[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n| subdivision_type5  = [[Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name5  = [[Lac-Jacques-Cartier, Quebec|Lac-Jacques-Cartier]]\n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             = {{convert|20,1|km|mi|abbr=on}} \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= \n| discharge1_min     = \n| discharge1_avg     = \n| discharge1_max     = \n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = Fourchu lake\n| source1_location   = [[Lac-Jacques-Cartier, Quebec|Lac-Jacques-Cartier]]\n| source1_coordinates= {{coord|47.33381|-70.90714|type:river_region:CA-QC|format=dms|display=inline}}\n| source1_elevation  = 806 m\n| mouth              = [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)]]\n| mouth_location     = [[Lac-Jacques-Cartier, Quebec|Lac-Jacques-Cartier]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = {{coord|47.2275|-70.81389|type:river_region:CA-QC|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| mouth_elevation    = 370 m\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = \n| basin_size         = \n| tributaries_left   =(Upward from the mouth) Three unidentified streams, Lac de la Tour outlet, Caribou lake outlet.\n| tributaries_right  =(Upward from the mouth) Small unidentified stream, outlet of Lac Janot, outlet of Lac Br\u00fbl\u00e9.\n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = \n}}\nThe '''Rivi\u00e8re Br\u00fbl\u00e9''' is a tributary of the [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)|Sainte-Anne River]], flowing on the north bank of the [[Saint Lawrence River]], in the non-territory organized from [[Lac-Jacques-Cartier, Quebec|Lac-Jacques-Cartier]], in the [[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]], in the administrative region of [[Capitale-Nationale]], in the [[provinces and territories of Canada|province]] of [[Quebec]], in [[Canada]].\n\nThe southern part of this small valley is served on each side of the river by various forest roads. The upper part is served by a forest road which passes on the north side of the river. Forestry is the main economic activity in this valley; recreational tourism, second.\n\nThe surface of the Br\u00fbl\u00e9 River is generally frozen from the beginning of December until the end of March; however, safe traffic on the ice is generally from mid-December to mid-March. The upper part has a freezing period of about an additional week. The water level of the river varies with the seasons and the precipitation; the spring flood occurs in March or April.\n\n== Geography ==\nThe Br\u00fbl\u00e9 River takes its source at the confluence of Lake Fourchu, in the unorganized territory of [[Lac-Jacques-Cartier]]. This lake has a marsh area on the west side and a high cliff on the north side and on the south side. The mouth of this lake is located at:\n* {{convert|4.6|km}} east of the course of the [[Savane River (Rivi\u00e8re des Neiges)|Savane River]];\n* {{convert|6.3|km}} west of the summit of Mont Raoul-Blanchard (altitude: {{convert|1159|m}});\n* {{convert|5.8|km}} northwest of the summit of Mont Bleu (altitude: {{convert|1150|m}});\n* {{convert|13.8|km}} north-west of the mouth of the Br\u00fbl\u00e9 river.\n\nFrom the mouth of Lac Fourchu, the course of the Br\u00fbl\u00e9 river descends on {{convert|20.1|km}}, with a drop of {{convert|436|m}}, according to the following segments:\n* {{convert|1,5|km}} east to the outlet (coming from the south) of Lac Br\u00fbl\u00e9;\n* {{convert|3.0|km}} to the east in a deep valley, up to a bend in the river;\n* {{convert|6,4|km}} to the south in a deep valley passing on the west side of Mont Raoul-Blanchard and Br\u00fbl\u00e9 mountain, then bending east to end in a small valley, until '' at the outlet (coming from the west) of Lac Janot;\n* {{convert|7.1|km}} towards the south-east with a drop of {{convert|99|m}}, forming some serpentines at the end of the segment where the current crosses a long series of rapids, until at a bend in the river;\n* {{convert|2.1|km}} towards the northeast by crossing several series of rapids, to its mouth.<ref name=Atlas>[https://atlas.gc.ca/toporama/en /index.html Atlas of Canada - Department of Natural Resources Canada - Rivi\u00e8re Br\u00fbl\u00e9 - Distance and altitude measurements established from the application of site measurements.]</ref>\n\nThe Br\u00fbl\u00e9 river flows on the southwest shore of the [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)]], in the unorganized territory of [[Lac-Jacques-Cartier, Quebec|Lac-Jacques-Cartier]], facing the northern limit of [[Saint -Tite-des-Caps]]. This confluence is located {{convert|13.1|km}} west of the northwest shore of the [[St. Lawrence River]], {{convert|20.5|km}} south west of the village center of [[Petite-Rivi\u00e8re-Saint-Fran\u00e7ois]] and {{convert|10.0|km}} north-west of the village center of [[Saint-Tite-des-Caps]].\n\nFrom the confluence of the Br\u00fbl\u00e9 river, the current flows over {{convert|27.5|km}} generally towards the southwest by the course of the [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)|Sainte-Anne River]], which crosses downtown [[Beaupr\u00e9, Quebec|Beaupr\u00e9]], to the northwest shore of the [[Saint Lawrence River]].<ref name=Atlas/>\n\n== Toponymy ==\nProbably born around 1592 in Champigny-sur-Marne in France, \u00c9tienne Br\u00fbl\u00e9 became an explorer and an interpreter in the Wendat (Huron) language. He arrived in the colony at the same time as [[Samuel de Champlain]], with whom he enlisted in 1608. Br\u00fbl\u00e9 was possibly the first European to have entered [[Huronia]]. He explored several territories including [[Georgian Bay]] and Lakes Huron, Ontario, Superior and Erie, where he traded furs for the French. During the illegal capture of [[Quebec (city) Quebec]] by the Kirke brothers in 1629, in a context of war between England and France, \u00c9tienne Brul\u00e9 went to the service of the English. Finally, the [[Treaty of Saint-Germain-en-Laye]] put an end to the conflict by restoring [[New France]] to [[France]], in 1632. Samuel de Champlain returned to the colony and accuses \u00c9tienne Br\u00fbl\u00e9 of treason in these terms: \"Here are those who betrayed their Roy & sold their homeland[\u2026]\". \u00c9tienne Brul\u00e9 then took refuge in [[Huronia]] where he was killed, in the year 1633.\n\nThe toponym \"Rivi\u00e8re Br\u00fbl\u00e9\" was formalized on December 13, 1996 at the Place Names Bank of the Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec.<ref>[http://www.toponymie.gouv.qc.ca/ct/ToposWeb/fiche.aspx?no_seq=167145 Commission de toponymie du Qu\u00e9bec - Bank of Place Names - Toponym: Rivi\u00e8re Br\u00fbl\u00e9]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n* [[Capitale-Nationale]], an administrative region\n* [[La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n* [[Lac-Jacques-Cartier, Quebec|Lac-Jacques-Cartier]], an unorganized territory\n* [[Lac Br\u00fbl\u00e9 (Lac-Jacques-Cartier)]], a body of water\n* [[Sainte-Anne River (Beaupr\u00e9)]]\n* [[St. Lawrence River]]\n* [[List of rivers of Quebec]]\n\n{{Portal|Capitale-Nationale|lakes and streams}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Br\u00fbl\u00e9, river}}\n[[Category:Rivers of Capitale-Nationale]]\n[[Category:La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9 Regional County Municipality]]\n", "name_user": "Veillg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGeography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brul%C3%A9e_River_(Sainte-Anne_River_tributary)"}
{"title_page": "DCOP", "text_new": "{{for|the use of this acronym as it pertains to artificial intelligence|Distributed constraint optimization}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = \n| title                  = Desktop Communication Protocol\n| logo                   = <!-- Image name is enough -->\n| logo caption           = \n| logo_size              = \n| logo_alt               = \n| screenshot             = <!-- Image name is enough -->\n| caption                = \n| screenshot_size        = \n| screenshot_alt         = \n| collapsible            = \n| author                 = [[KDE]]\n| developer              = [[KDE]]\n| released               = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| discontinued           = yes\n| latest release version = \n| latest release date    = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date    = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| status                 = \n| programming language   = \n| operating system       = [[Linux]]\n| genre                  = [[Inter-process communication|IPC daemon]]\n| license                = [[GNU LGPL]]\n| website                = \n}}\n'''D'''esktop '''CO'''mmunication '''P'''rotocol ('''DCOP''') was an [[inter-process communication]] (IPC) [[Daemon (computing)|daemon]] by [[KDE]] used in [[K Desktop Environment 3]]. The design goal for the protocol was to allow [[Application software|applications]] to interoperate, and share complex tasks. Essentially, DCOP was a \u2018remote control\u2019 system, which allowed applications or scripts to enlist the help of other applications. DCOP is built on top of the [[X Window System protocols and architecture#Inter-client communication|X11 Inter-Client Exchange]] protocol.\n\nDCOP continues to be used by the K Desktop Environment 3-fork [[Trinity Desktop Environment]]. DCOP was replaced by [[D-Bus]], a message bus system heavily influenced by the DCOP and standardized by [[freedesktop.org]], in [[KDE Software Compilation 4]] and later.\n\n== DCOP model ==\nDCOP implements the [[client\u2013server model]], where each application using DCOP is a client and communicates with other clients through the DCOP server. DCOP server functions like a traffic director, dispatching messages/calls to the proper destinations. All clients are peers of each other.\n\nTwo types of actions are possible with DCOP: \"send and forget\" messages, which do not block, and \"calls,\" which block waiting for some data to be returned.\n\nAny data that will be sent is serialized (also referred to as ''[[Marshalling (computer science)|marshalling]]'' in [[CORBA]] speak) using the built-in QDataStream operators available in all of the [[Qt (software)|Qt]] [[Class (computer science)|classes]]. There is also a simple IDL-like compiler available (dcopidl and dcopidl2cpp) that generates stubs and skeletons. Using the dcopidl compiler has the additional benefit of [[type safety]].\n\nThere is a command-line tool called \u2018dcop\u2019 (note the lower-case letters) that can be used for communication with the applications from the shell. \u2018kdcop\u2019 is a [[Graphical user interface|GUI]] tool to explore the [[Interface (computer science)|interfaces]] of an application.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n* [[KDELibs]] \u2013 predecessor of KDE Platform 4\n\n==External links==\n* [http://api.kde.org/3.5-api/kdelibs-apidocs/dcop/html/index.html DCOP Documentation]\n\n{{Inter-process communication}}\n{{KDE}}\n\n[[Category:Inter-process communication]]\n[[Category:KDE Platform]]\n[[Category:Software that uses Qt]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the use of this acronym as it pertains to artificial intelligence|Distributed constraint optimization}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = \n| title                  = Desktop Communication Protocol\n| logo                   = <!-- Image name is enough -->\n| logo caption           = \n| logo_size              = \n| logo_alt               = \n| screenshot             = <!-- Image name is enough -->\n| caption                = \n| screenshot_size        = \n| screenshot_alt         = \n| collapsible            = \n| author                 = [[KDE]]\n| developer              = [[KDE]]\n| released               = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| discontinued           = yes\n| latest release version = \n| latest release date    = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date    = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| status                 = \n| programming language   = \n| operating system       = [[Linux]]\n| genre                  = [[Inter-process communication|IPC daemon]]\n| license                = [[GNU LGPL]]\n| website                = \n}}\n'''D'''esktop '''CO'''mmunication '''P'''rotocol ('''DCOP''') was an [[inter-process communication]] (IPC) [[Daemon (computing)|daemon]] by [[KDE]] used in [[K Desktop Environment 3]]. The design goal for the protocol was to allow [[Application software|applications]] to interoperate, and share complex tasks. Essentially, DCOP was a \u2018remote control\u2019 system, which allowed applications or scripts to enlist the help of other applications. DCOP is built on top of the [[X Window System protocols and architecture#Inter-client communication|X11 Inter-Client Exchange]] protocol.\n\nDCOP continues to be used by the K Desktop Environment 3-fork [[Trinity Desktop Environment]]. DCOP was replaced by [[D-Bus]], a message bus system heavily influenced by the DCOP and standardized by [[freedesktop.org]], in [[KDE Software Compilation 4]] and later.\n\n== DCOP model ==\nDCOP implements the [[client\u2013server model]], where each application using DCOP is a client and communicates with other clients through the DCOP server. DCOP server functions like a traffic director, dispatching messages/calls to the proper destinations. All clients are peers of each other.\n\nTwo types of actions are possible with DCOP: \"send and forget\" messages, which do not block, and \"calls,\" which block waiting for some data to be returned.\n\nAny data that will be sent is serialized (also referred to as ''[[Marshalling (computer science)|marshalling]]'' in [[CORBA]] speak) using the built-in QDataStream operators available in all of the [[Qt (software)|Qt]] [[Class (computer science)|classes]]. There is also a simple IDL-like compiler available (dcopidl and dcopidl2cpp) that generates stubs and skeletons. Using the dcopidl compiler has the additional benefit of [[type safety]].\n\nThere is a command-line tool called \u2018dcop\u2019 (note the lower-case letters) that can be used for communication with the applications from the shell. \u2018kdcop\u2019 is a [[Graphical user interface|GUI]] tool to explore the [[Interface (computer science)|interfaces]] of an application.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n* [[KDELibs]] \u2013 predecessor of KDE Platform 4\n\n==External links==\n* [http://api.kde.org/3.5-api/kdelibs-apidocs/dcop/html/index.html DCOP Documentation]\n\n{{IPC}}\n{{KDE}}\n\n[[Category:Inter-process communication]]\n[[Category:KDE Platform]]\n[[Category:Software that uses Qt]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DCOP"}
{"title_page": "Petraio", "text_new": "[[File:Naples_Petraio.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:The Petraio Naples Italy-02.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 03.jpeg|thumb|300px|Salita del Petraio, Pensione Haase]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 04.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\nThe '''Petraio''' is a widely-known urban path in [[Naples, Italy]], which descends from what was once an expansive upper agricultural area (the present day hilltop district of [[Vomero]]) and connects with lower neighborhoods before terminating in the [[Chiaia]] neighborhood of downtown Naples. \n\nFomerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref> the path was originally a natural, self-formed alluvial channel that followed a narrow watershed, deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As these areas were trafficked and inhabited, the path was improved to a narrow series of interconnected stone walks, alleys, steps and ramps &mdash; varying in slope and width, at points overarched by buildings.<ref name=\"pet8\">{{cite web\n |title        = Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders\n |publisher    = repubblica.it\n |author       = Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata\n |date         = January 14, 2014\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fespresso.repubblica.it%2Fvisioni%2Fcultura%2F2014%2F01%2F14%2Fnews%2Fnapoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref> \n\nProminent sub-sections include:<br/>\n*Gradini (steps) del Petraio<br/>\n*Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio<br/>\n*Vico (alley) del Petraio<br/>\n*Largo (widening) del Petraio<br/>\n*Rampe (ramp) del Petraio<br/>\n*Salita (climb) del Petraio<br/> \n\nFramed with residential buildings, churches,and small businesses, the Petraio is accessibly only on foot, and is noted for its broad range of architecture &mdash; from [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] villas to its ''bassi,'' small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself &mdash; as well as its picturesque character and sweeping views of the city.\n\n==Access==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed via streets in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]]. The Petraio is served by the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] as well by the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]].  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' prominent Corso Vittorio Emanuele.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref> \n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}} \n\nThe Petraio are a subset of Naples more than 200 neighborhood stairs, ramps and pedestrian descents.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss-born painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of \u200b\u200bGenoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla , which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli .\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See Also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Italy|Naples stairways]]\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Naples_Petraio.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:The Petraio Naples Italy-02.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 03.jpeg|thumb|300px|Salita del Petraio, Pensione Haase]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 04.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\nThe '''Petraio''' is a widely-known urban path in [[Naples, Italy]], which descends from what was once an expansive upper agricultural area (the present day hilltop district of [[Vomero]]) and connects with lower neighborhoods before terminating in the [[Chiaia]] neighborhood of downtown Naples. \n\nFomerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref> the path was originally a natural, self-formed alluvial channel that followed a narrow watershed, deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As these areas were trafficked and inhabited, the path was improved to a narrow series of interconnected stone walks, alleys, steps and ramps &mdash; varying in slope and width, at points overarched by buildings.<ref name=\"pet8\">{{cite web\n |title        = Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders\n |publisher    = repubblica.it\n |author       = Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata\n |date         = January 14, 2014\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fespresso.repubblica.it%2Fvisioni%2Fcultura%2F2014%2F01%2F14%2Fnews%2Fnapoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref> \n\nProminent sub-sections include:<br/>\n*Gradini (steps) del Petraio<br/>\n*Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio<br/>\n*Vico (alley) del Petraio<br/>\n*Largo (widening) del Petraio<br/>\n*Rampe (ramp) del Petraio<br/>\n*Salita (climb) del Petraio<br/> \n\nFramed with residential buildings, churches,and small businesses, the Petraio is accessibly only on foot, and is noted for its broad range of architecture, from [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] villas to its ''bassi'' (small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself) &mdash; as well as its picturesque character and sweeping views of the city.\n\n==Access==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed via streets in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]]. The Petraio is served by the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] as well by the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]].  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' prominent Corso Vittorio Emanuele.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref> \n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}} \n\nThe Petraio are a subset of Naples more than 200 neighborhood stairs, ramps and pedestrian descents.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss-born painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of \u200b\u200bGenoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla , which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli .\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See Also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Italy|Naples stairways]]\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petraio"}
